ents and decisions that led them to the Charleston Orphan House through the children’s time spent there to, in a few cases, their later adult lives. What these accounts reveal are families struggling to maintain ties after catastrophic loss and to preserve bonds with children who no longer lived under their roofs. An intimate glimpse into the lives of the white poor in early American history, The Charleston Orphan House is moreover an illuminating look at social welfare provision in the antebellum South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOrphanageszSouth CarolinazCharlestonxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  achildren, childhood, growing up, coming of age, orphans, orphanage, public, america, american, united states, welfare, poverty, south, southern, benefactors, apprentice, social studies, community, inequality, equality, class, classism, politics, political, family, true story, history, historical, antebellum, carolina, education, sickness, adulthood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692409040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226924106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226924106/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles